    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-07-07T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-07-07T05:00:00-05:00" n="1231"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1231">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">701.0066A/7–744: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Algiers</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lawton</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Algiers</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-07-07T12:00:00+02:00"
                            >July 7, 1944—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 10:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2313. From Murphy. Reference my 2221, July 1, 1 p.m. Alexander’s Headquarters
                    report that in agreement with Control Commission they plan to arrange transfer
                    to Palermo on July 10 of Axis diplomats to Holy See who have not entered
                    Vatican. Pending repatriation they will be suitably accommodated under guard in
                        Palermo.<note n="77" xml:id="d1231fn1">The Axis diplomats were housed at the
                        Hotel Miramar at Taormina instead of Palermo as originally planned.</note>
                </p>
                <p>In absence of contrary instructions it is intended to release von Kessel to enter
                    Vatican and to send Wemmer and Elling<note n="78" xml:id="d1231fn2">Georg
                        Elling, Attaché of the German Embassy, with the title of
                        Wissenschaftmitarbeiter.</note> to Palermo since it is considered most
                    desirable to remove these two from Rome as soon as possible<note n="79"
                        xml:id="d1231fn3">Both diplomats were under suspicion as being German
                        intelligence agents. Allied Force Headquarters accumulated evidence to show
                        that Elling was a member of the Sicherheitsdienst charged with directing
                        occupational espionage.</note> and such action will not prejudice their
                    ultimate disposal.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Naples for Kirk.<note n="80" xml:id="d1231fn4">Alexander C. Kirk.
                        American Representative on the Advisory Council for Italy. Mr. Kirk
                        transmitted the substance of this telegram to Myron C. Taylor at Rome in a
                        letter dated July 8.</note> [Murphy.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lawton</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
